                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/323.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Special
                        Agent <persName type="to">Carothers</persName>.</hi>
                    <note n="123" xml:id="d1422fn123">Similar telegram to the American Consul at
                        Tampico</note>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 13, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Spanish Ambassador reports receipt of information that Constitutionalists at
                    Tampico continue to impose forced loans on Spaniards and have arrested Juan
                    Isusi and Ramon Junco for refusing to pay. According to Ambassador’s advices
                    authorities style these loans as voluntary contributions and this may explain
                    why they have denied that such loans were being imposed.</p>
                <p>Use your good offices with General Carranza to end that imposition these forced
                    loans be abandoned and that Spaniards under arrest be released.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
